Indonesia Stock Movers: Astra, Bank Central Asia, Semen Gresik

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-07-01T09:48:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-01/indonesia-stock-movers-astra-bank-central-asia-semen-gresik.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  advanced 38.53 points, or 1
percent, to a record 3,927.1. The measure rose 2 percent in the
holiday-shortened week.  Banks: PT Bank Rakyat Indonesia (BBRI IJ), the nation’s
biggest bank by revenue, gained 3.1 percent to a record 6,700
rupiah. PT Bank Central Asia (BBCA IJ), the largest by market
value, advanced 2 percent to 7,800 rupiah.  Indonesia’s inflation slowed for a fifth straight month in
June, easing pressure on the central bank to raise borrowing
costs. June consumer prices rose 5.54 percent from a year
earlier after climbing 5.98 percent in May, the central bureau
of statistics said today.  PT Astra International (ASII IJ), Indonesia’s largest
automotive retailer, rose 3.2 percent to 66,550 rupiah, the
highest close since at least August 1991. CLSA Asia-Pacific
Markets increased the company’s share-price estimate by 17
percent to 75,000 rupiah, saying Astra is a “key proxy to the
region’s consumption story.”  PT Bumi Resources (BUMI IJ),  Indonesia ’s biggest coal
producer, advanced 1.7 percent to 3,000 rupiah, the biggest
increase since June 22. Bumi said its $1.9 billion debt payment
to China Investment Corp. isn’t dependent on the issuance of
convertible bonds by shareholder Bumi Plc. The shareholder said
June 10 it will issue convertible bonds for Bumi in return for a
75 percent stake in a metal-mining unit.  PT Semen Gresik (SMGR IJ), Indonesia’s biggest cement
producer, rose 2.6 percent to 9,850 rupiah, the steepest gain
since April 1. The company plans to buy a 20 percent stake or
more in paper producer PT Kertas Kraft Aceh, Investor Daily
Indonesia reported, citing a person it didn’t identify. Semen
Gresik President Director Dwi Soetjipto couldn’t be reached when
called at his office in Gresik, East Java.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
